Configure %s to automatically keep itself up-to-date to better handle newer spyware, adware, and other malware threats. Although you can manually search for %s updates, you may find it more convenient to have %s automatically perform this task and download updates for you. This helps ensure you have the latest protection.

When you clean malware from your machine with %s, it may determine that certain tasks need to be stopped as it deletes malware-related files from your system. Normally this process happens automatically.

Adware, which often is synonymous with spyware, is spyware that monitors your access for the intent of delivering advertisements. Spyware may display pop-up advertisements no matter what software you are using, but most spyware instead hooks into your web browser to deliver advertisements based on where you travel on the Internet.

If you visit websites that install spyware on your machines or install software that secretly contains spyware, it is highly unlikely that you will be infected by just one type of spyware. Most of the time, infections involve several different spyware programs that, when running simultaneously, cause system instability and software crashes.

Your machine may have a known security exploit, known to hackers, but not necessarily to you. If you do not keep your operating system and software up-to-date, a firewall can sometimes help prevent malicious people from exploiting the vulnerabilities on your machine.

If your machine does become infected, firewalls, if configured and updated, can help prevent spyware or adware "calling home" so that advertisements are not delivered to your machine and your computer use is not monitored and recorded.

Spyware and adware, when installed, may open holes on your machine through which other threats can enter. A correctly configured and updated firewall can block many of these holes, helping to prevent other malware from infecting your computer.

If you have noticed that your browser's home page and/or search pages have changed, possibly to a search engine you do not recognize or to a website you cannot remember viewing, be careful. There is a chance you may be infected with spyware and adware.

Malicious software packages exist on the Internet that attempt to gain complete control over computer systems. These programs, sometimes called Remote Access Trojans (RAT) or Backdoor Software  are sometimes attached to Trojan Horses, viruses, worms, and spyware exploits. If your system is infected, there is virtually no limit to what these programs can do.

AceBot is a hazardous backdoor Trojan, which was designed for performing a lot of different destructive actions. First of all, this Trojan is able to detect and disable antivirus applications, installed on the target computer; this technique is very dangerous, because this allows many spywares easily infect the machine. Moreover, AceBot may also connect to ICR client and use it for giving the intruder a remote control over the computer. AceBot is a real threat for user's sensitive information, because the hacker automatically gets an access to it. Finally, AceBot is also able to connect to many servers and download spywares from there.

This application was created using Delphi programming language. It was created in July 2000. The author is a Brazilian software developer ROGAN. This is a newer version of A-Trojan. It has all the same abilities the previous version had, and a "backdoor" function was added. It means that the trojan installs a security breach, through which a full access to user's PC is possible.

IpWins is an adware application. Once installed on your PC, IpWins parasite will generate a large volume of popup adverts, and may trigger browser slowdowns and crashes. Additionally, IpWins parasite opens up a security hole on your computer by which other adware and Trojan applications can be installed. IpWins is a serious security risk and should be removed immediately.

BackWeb is software that automatically updates your computer. There are two different versions of BackWeb. One is used by computer manufacturers to connect to your computer and retrieve non-personal data which they use to make sure your system is up to date. The other version, BackWeb Lite, may launch pop-up advertisements and install unknown software without your authorization.

Adlogix is a complex adware program that serves annoying commercial advertisements and pop-ups. Adlogix silently updates itself via the Internet. Its main component works as a computer driver and therefore is very difficult to detect and completely disable.

It is an illegal advertising application that secretly works in background and shows undesirable commercial information. Advware.Adstart.b shows advertisements in numerous pop-ups, web browser windows or toolbars. It can get into the computer from unsafe web sites. Some ad-supported softwares include it as a component. Advware.Adstart.b doesn't possess any serious threat to the computer security, but may severely violate user privacy.
The purpose or the source of Msiebho is unknown. May be related to ClientMan. Likely to slow performance of Internet Explorer.

MPower can secretly get into the computer from several malicious web sites or come along with free ad-supported software. Its main task is to serve commercial advertisements to user desktop or within related application. MPower modifies essential computer and, sometimes, browser settings without asking for user permission, so the adware could start automatically on every Windows startup and work hidden in background. MPower doesn't compromise computer security, but obstructs usual web surfing and may violate user privacy by tracking his Internet activity.

NavExcel adware shows undesirable commercial advertisements and sends a web browser to certain sites. NavExcel rather is the unwanted application than actual spyware. It must be manually installed or may arrive with some third-party software. NavExcel runs every time the user launches Internet Explorer.

PerMedia is an adware spyware that shows unexpected pop-up advertisements while you surf the Internet. The threat sends e-mail messages to all the contacts in the Microsoft Outlook address book. These letters contain links leading to the web site that distributes PerMedia. The adware can download from the Internet and install unsolicited potentially harmful software. It also has the ability to automatically update itself. PerMedia can get into the computer while visiting some web resources, which links are distributed by e-mail.

PopMonster is an adware spyware designed to show annoying advertisements in web browser windows, pop-ups or undesirable toolbars. PopMonster can be distributed with ad-supported software, some malicious sites may install to the computer without user permission. PopMonster receives commercial data and updates from its home servers. On occasion PopMonster can perform additional malicious actions, such as browser hijacking or tracking user activity in the Internet. PopMonster threat is able to start automatically on every Windows startup and remain hidden in background. PopMonster's activities violate user privacy and affects computer performance.

Backdoor.IRCBot is a Trojan backdoor that uses the MS06-040 vulnerability to propagate itself throughout a network. Backdoor.IRCBot attempts to connect to IRC through which he would receive commands from a remote host. Then the remote hacker may instruct Backdoor.IRCBot to record all the keystrokes that you type, to launch denial of service attacks, or send spam emails. Backdoor.IRCBot is a serious security risk to your personal and financial data and we recommend its removal immediately.
A quite dangerous backdoor. A server application writes itself to your PC, and then a hacker can get remote access to it. Connects to your PC through 31416 or other port.

This backdoor, as majority of these pests, consists of a server and a client application. Server writes itself into the Windows folder as a file nwc.exe, and then a hacker can get access to your PC remotely.

Backdoor.Mechbot is a backdoor spyware which poses a real danger to your private information. Once installed, Backdoor.Mechbot will allow the remote attacker to gain full access to your machine over the Internet. The remote hacker then may perform nasty activities, such as stealing your sensitive data including passwords. Backdoor.Mechbot is a major security threat and should be removed immediately to protect your confidential data.

Backdoor.Agobot.agl is a network-worm that distributes denial of service and backdoor capabilities. Backdoor.Agobot.agl propagates through network shares protected by weak passwords and by exploiting vulnerabilities. Once it is executed, Backdoor.Agobot.agl will automatically launch with Windows and can be used by a remote attacker to launch Denial of Service attacks on other computers and networks. Backdoor.Agobot.agl may shut down or circumvent anti-virus and other security-related utilities.

Akbot is an IRC-controlled backdoor, which provides the attacker with unauthorized remote access to the compromised PC. The intruder can gain control over the computer and steal user sensitive information. He can also access certain Internet resources and setup a hidden proxy server. Akbot automatically runs on every Windows startup.

NetTrojan offers an unauthorized user access and control of your computer. Through NetTrojan, an anonymous user may spy on your computer activity, upload software onto your system, and download and delete files stored on your hard drive.

IBIS Toolbar is a web browser toolbar that may redirect your search requests and display pop-up advertisements. IBIS Toolbar may monitor your Internet activity, including your search requests, websites you are visiting, products you are buying, and data you enter into forms. IBIS Toolbar may share this information with third party partners. IBIS Toolbar may also download and install adware without your knowledge or permission. IBIS Toolbar may prevent you from visiting various anti-spyware websites. IBIS Toolbar is typically distributed through pop-up advertisements and bundles with other spyware, such as Cydoor.

Findwhatever is a browser hijacker that periodically changes Internet Explorer default home page to many advertising web sites. Findwhatever doesn't have any harmful payload. It can silently get into the computer while visiting certain web pages. The spyware runs on every Windows startup.

Hmtoolbar is an Internet Explorer toolbar designed to serve undesirable commercial advertisements. It also downloads from the Internet and runs unsolicited third-party software without user knowledge and permission. Hmtoolbar must be manually installed. It runs every time the user launches Internet Explorer.

eStart is a an Internet Explorer toolbar that replaces the web browser's default Links toolbar, creates links to many web sites and adds some bookmarks to the Favorites list. The threat examines user e-mail messages, steals found identity details such as user's full name and silently sends gathered data to remote web servers. eStart can update itself via the Internet, download and install unsolicited potentially harmful applications. It also may attempt to monitor user Internet activity and suggest sponsored links once a particular keyword is detected. eStart is bundled with some ad-supported softwares.

GonnaSearch is an Internet Explorer toolbar providing a web search service and pop-up blocker. It intercepts Internet searches and sends a web browser to undesirable web sites. GonnaSearch is bundled with some advertising-supported products. It can also be manually installed. The threat runs every time the user launches Internet Explorer.

MWSearch is a simple Internet Explorer search toolbar. It offers a web search service, but also may show undesirable commercial advertisements. MWSearch doesn't have dangerous payload. It runs every time the user opens Internet Explorer.

OrbitExplorer is an Internet Explorer search toolbar that changes web browser's default home and search pages and adds multiple bookmars to the Favorites list. The threat silently downloads and installs several adware softwares without asking for user permission. It also can send a web browser to advertising web sites. OrbitExplorer has the ability to update itself via the Internet. The threat must be manually installed. It automatically runs on every Windows startup.

PowerStrip is an Internet Explorer toolbar that downloads and installs files without your consent. While using a merchant site, PowerStrip can secretly switch affiliate IDs to steal commission fees from your web shopping. PowerStrip can automatically update itself and send collected data to it's remote server. PowerStrip may prove difficult to remove manually and may come bundled with other malware.

SpotOn is a browser plugin that claims to enable you to surf faster, create WebTours and organize bookmarks. SpotOn is a component that Internet Explorer will load whenever it starts, shares IE's memory context, can perform any action on the available windows and modules.

Proxybar is an Internet Explorer toolbar that allows the user to choose and use certain proxy servers. However, it also shows commercial pop-up advertisements and intercepts web searches sending the web browser to undesirable web sites. Proxybar must be manually installed. It runs every time the user launches Internet Explorer.

It is an Internet Explorer toolbar that provides a web search service and pop-up blocker and also shows links to many, mostly adult web sites. Cram Toolbar changes the Internet Explorer default home page to a pornographic site and alters web browser's configuration. The threat is related to the infamous cracks.am site, which distributes illegal cracks for popular software. Cram Toolbar must be manually installed. It runs every time the user launches Internet Explorer.

This application overloads the connection by pinging. That causes a DoS attack. A DoS attack means ''Denial of Service'' attack. The flooder is sending a big load of useless data to the messenger, or constantly pings the server.

This MSN Messenger flooder overloads the server by continuous pinging. That causes a DoS attack. Flooders can jam the IRC connection or even corrupt some vital files, such as registry, key files etc. Such applications are often used on IRC channels to disturb communications. However, almost every self-respecting IRC channel is protected by special Flood detection algorithms. It was created in April 2002.

This application overloads the connection by pinging. That causes a DoS attack. DoS attacks may affect the work of your server or jam IRC channels. However, almost every self-respecting IRC channel is protected by special Flood detection algorithms. Flooders also may contain some pesky 'backdoor' or 'nuker' applications. It was created in April, 1997, and needs at least 5 Kb for storage.

Such a flooder can completely freeze your server with a DoS attack. It pings the server continuously until it crashes. A flooder can also contain other trojan functions or install a 'backdoor' that provides the hacker full access to your PC. This flooder was created in April 2003, it needs at least 405 Kb for storage.

This application overloads the connection by pinging. That causes a DoS attack. It sends a large amount of worthless data and jams yours IRC and MSN messenger. Most IRC channels have special flood-tracking algorithms, but flooders still remain a problem. The origination date is March, 2002, it needs 433 Kb for storage.

Such flooders are often used to disturb communications. This application overloads the IRC connection by continuously sending a large amount of data. That way it jams the channel or reduces the connection speed critically. However, almost every self-respecting IRC channel is protected by special Flood detection algorithms.

This flooder is designed for freezing servers by constant pinging. It causes a DoS attack. Some flooders are designed for jamming IRC and MSN channels. Such pesky applications can also contain some nasty 'surprises' such as 'backdoors' trojans etc. This flooder was created in November, 1994.

This flooder can make some serious damage to your PC, as it installs a mIRC client with 'backdoor' function. That way the hacker can gain unlimited access to your machine. Many versions appeared from May, 2002 to April, 2004. They all share the same abilities.

This application is designed as a trojan which sends a big amount of useless data to a specified PC. Such applications are often used on IRC channels to disturb communications. However, almost every self-respecting IRC channel is protected by special Flood detection algorithms. The primary function of flooders is DoS attack. This ICMP flooder was created in October, 2002.

This application overloads the connection by pinging. That causes a DoS attack. 'DoS' attack means 'Denial of Service'. It is a way to prevent users of using some kind of service. Hackers usually try to corrupt the work of server, or 'flood' your messenger But flooders can also be used for e-mail flooding.

ACXInstall is a malicious ActiveX control that silently gets into the computer while visiting some insecure web sites. It downloads from the Internet and installs arbitrary software without asking for user permission. ACXInstall usually drops dialers that connect a compromised PC to the Internet through premium rate phone numbers. These dialers provide access to mostly pornographic web resources.

Dropper-Delf is a Spyware Trojan designed to infiltrate your computer and open a conduit by which large amounts of adware and spyware can be piped to your system. Dropper-Delf opens up a large security hole on your computer and is a very dangerous threat to the security of your personal and financial data. Dropper-Delf will download and install numerous additional parasites.

Winamp, a popular media player, has a critical vulnerability, which can be utilized by the Exploit.winamp.pls exploit. This threat installs widely spread spywares and a variant of the CoolWebSearch hijacker to the compromised computer. The following manual removal instructions should be used in order to eliminate the spywares that Exploit.winamp.pls drops. To prevent the infection update to Winamp, which includes a fix for the vulnerability.

Mal/Iframe is a nasty malware that is designed to spread throughout the Internet. Mal/Iframe is a textbook example of a dangerous Web threat that hijacks and exploits vulnerable sites not considering whether the content is about cookery or pornography. In addition, hackers may embed Mal/Iframe into e-mails using HTML to exploit users.

First4DRM is a rootkit, which cloaks any running processes, files, directories and registry keys that begin with the $sys$ string. It prevents installed softwares and computer tools from accessing hidden objects, so that only specific processes beginning with the same $sys$ string can access them. The rooktit is a part of XCP Content Manager, which is the legitimate software used to protect digital media from unauthorized duplication, publishing, etc. This software is distributed on some Sony BMG DRM-protected music CDs. Once the user inserts such a disc into the PC's CD or DVD drive, XCP secretly installs Firt4DRM to the computer. It does it without the user's knowledge and explicit consent. Although First4DRM is not an actual malware, it behaves as a spyware, can be easily used to hide real risks and therefore is classified as a malicious unsolicited application. It automatically runs as a service on every Windows startup.

Virtool.DoS.Synte.A is a tool employed by virus and malware makers. They may use Virtool.DoS.Synte.A to pack the executable files using UPX technology. Virtool.DoS.Synte.A employs UPX (Ultimate Packer for eXecutables) so that antivirus applications cannot see what is inside an infected file.

Envolo is a malicious application that silently downloads and installs adware spywares. It also can update already installed pests. In some cases Envolo may severely degrade PC performance or even crash the computer due bugs in its code. The threat is bundled with some spywares and ad-supported software. It can also be manually installed. Envolo automatically runs on every Windows startup.

Aenima is a mail bomber designed to send large amount of anonymous e-mail messages and spam. This spyware can be used to flood certain PCs, overload mail servers or local network. Aenima can send e-mails with different header, body or attached files. The spyware doesn't distribute itself and must be manually installed. Its presence in the computer indicates that your PC was compromised and now is used as an illegal mail server.
FakeMailer is a hacking tool designed to send forged emails from your computer. Fake-Mailer program may also come bundled with additional malware.

AdStartup is an adware program that monitors your web surfing habits and then transmits this information back to its parent server in order to build a marketing profile associated with your computer. AdStartup is a variant of AdLogix. In some cases, this parasite is installed with a rootkit to prevent detection and removal.

Adware.BHO.je is an adware component that is designed to install onto your PC as a BHO (Browser Helper Object). Once executed, Adware.BHO.je will display you annoying popup advertisements and redirect browser to 404 error pages.

Backdoor.Hupigon.mqe is a backdoor spyware which poses a real danger to your private information. Once installed, Backdoor.Hupigon.mqe will allow the remote attacker to gain full access to your machine over the Internet. The remote hacker then may perform nasty activities, such as stealing your sensitive data including passwords. Backdoor.Hupigon.mqe is a major security threat and should be removed immediately to protect your confidential data.

Adrotator.IconAds is a rogue adware application that installs itself as a Browser Helper Object (BHO). Once it is installed, Adrotator.IconAds launches on Windows startup and popups exaggerated security alerts to scare you into buying the full version of the program. Adrotator.IconAds may cause serious crashes of network and your PC.

BookedSpace is an adware application that installs itself on your computer, often without your consent (possibly bundled with another adware program). Once activated, BookedSpace will display popup adverts while you browse the web. BookedSpace will load itself automatically each time Windows starts. This adware also sends the URLs of pages that you visit to the company's parent servers in order to create a marketing profile through which to serve you ads. BookedSpace may also silently download and install other adware programs without your knowledge or consent.

Adware.ZToolbar installs itself on your PC without consent as an IE toolbar, and is often bundled with malicious software packages. Adware.ZToolbar BHO may generate excessive popup ads, reset your homepage and redirect your web searches. Adware.ZToolbar can be very difficult to manually remove, and has the ability to download and install other questionable and potentially dangerous programs onto your PC.

E2Give is a browser helper object (BHO) that may monitor your Internet activity, including which websites you are visiting and for how long you are visiting them. E2Give may also collect information about yourself and your computer, including your country, zip code, first name, etc. E2Give may redirect your search requests to various ecommerce sites in order to collect commissions. When you visit these ecommerce sites, E2Give may launch pop-up advertisements.
Meridian Pop-Upper is an Internet Explorer browser helper object that may launch pop-up advertising. Meridian may be installed as a drive-by download, without your consent or knowledge.

SearchFast is an Internet Explorer BHO that may have come bundled with a third party program. Once installed on your machine, Search Fast will load each time you open Internet Explorer.SearchFast may cause browser slowdown and instability.
Iggsey Toolbar is a BHO that changes Internet Explorer home page and redirects to Iggsey search page if internet address entered incorrectly
